<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos bakeri </i>varies in height from < 1 to 3 m. Its leaves are bright green in color and lightly hairy, and their shape is elliptic to obovate and usually rounded or truncate at base. It is similar to <i>A. stanfordiana </i>in appearance, but lacks noticeably hairy leaves. It lacks a lignotuber and is an obligate seeder. <i>A. bakeri </i>is a serpentine endemic, including ssp. <i>bakeri </i>(a CNPS list 1B.1 plant) and ssp. <i>sublaevis </i>(a CNPS list 1B.2 plant). Both are restricted to serpentine outcrops in the lower North Coast Ranges of Sonoma Co. (Best et al. 1996). <i>A. bakeri</i> ssp. <i>bakeri</i> grows between Camp Meeker and Occidental in Sonoma Co.  <i>A. bakeri </i>ssp. <i>sublaevis</i> is a member of the serpentine chaparral that is associated with groves of <i>Hesperocyparis sargentii</i> in The Cedars ACEC (managed by BLM).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Arctostaphylos montana </i>is a prostrate to mounded, evergreen shrub that lacks a lignotuber. Seeds collect in the duff and ground in a seed bank as stones as plants age. Seeds germinate when heated. Plants can reproduce by layering. <i>Arctostaphylos montana </i>ssp. <i>montana </i>(a CNPS list 1B.3 plant) has fewer than 20 occurrences in Marin Co. The majority are on the northern slopes of Mount Tamalpais on Marin Municipal Water District lands, covering just over 600 ha (Evens and Kentner 2006). Ssp. <i>ravenii </i>(a CNPS list 1B.1 plant) is a single clone at the Presidio in San Francisco. Older taxonomy included the name <i>A. hookeri </i>ssp. <i>montana, </i>but more recent work (Markos et al. 1998) suggests that only the southern subspecies should be maintained in <i>A. hookeri </i>(Parker et al. 2007, 2012).<br/>
<br/>
Stands of both <i>A. bakeri </i>ssp<i>. bakeri </i> and<i>A. montana </i>are restricted to serpentine substrates. While they are part of maritime chaparral (see maritime chaparral discussion in the Changes Since the First Edition section), they are in relatively xeric, rocky settings. They have been combined into a single alliance (Klein et al. 2015) since the 2009 publication of <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>.<br/>
<br/>
Stands have several rare plants occurring in the alliance. They include the CNPS List 1B plants <i>Lessingia micradenia </i>var. <i>micradenia, Streptanthus batrachopus, </i>and <i>S. glandulosus </i>ssp. <i>pulchellus; </i>the CNPS List 3 plant <i>Eriogonum luteolum </i>var. <i>caninum; </i>the CNPS List 4 plants <i>Calamagrostis ophitidis </i>and <i>Calochortus umbellatus</i>, among others. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
