<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">The historic fire cycle of chaparral on Mount Tamalpais may be similar to stands of maritime chaparral on the central coast, which is 10 to 100 years (Greenlee and Langenheim 1990); however, the fire return interval to maintain the obligate-seeding manzanita on serpentine is likely to be 50 to 100 years. Infrequent fire may result in encroachment of trees and a decline in shrubs and their seed banks. Conversely, serpentine rock outcrops with skeletal soils will experience slow tree encroachment. Frequent fire tends to convert manzanita stands to coastal scrub, seral scrub, or grassland.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (50-100+ years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
